content:
 PENSIVE, as she gazed upon the lifeless, I heard the Mother of All,  
Desperate, looking at the shattered bodies, at the forms that lay across battlefields;  
(As the final gun fell silent—but the scent of gunpowder still hung in the air;)  
As she called to her earth with a sorrowful voice while she moved:  
Embrace them well, O my earth, she implored—do not lose my sons! do not lose a single atom;  
And you streams, take them in well, absorbing their cherished blood;  
And you local places, and you breezes that float above lightly,  
And all you essences of soil and growth—and you, depths of my rivers;  
And you, mountain slopes—and the forests where my beloved children's blood, trickling, stained red;  
And you trees, deep in your roots, to pass on to all future trees,  
My dead absorb—my young men's beautiful bodies absorb—and their precious, precious, precious blood;  
Which, holding in trust for me, will faithfully return to me, many years later,  
In unseen essence and fragrance of surface and grass, centuries later;  
In the breezes from the fields, return to me my darlings—give me my immortal heroes;  
Exhale them to me centuries later—breathe their breath to me—let not a single atom be lost;  
O years and graves! O air and soil! O my dead, a sweet aroma!  
Exhale them eternally, sweet death, years, centuries later.

Rewritten:
PENSIVE, on her dead gazing, I heard Mother of All,
Desperate, on torn bodies, on the forms covering battle-
fields gazing;
(As the last gun ceased--but the scent of powder-smoke linger'd;)
As she call'd to her earth with mournful voice while she stalk'd:
Absorb them well, O my earth, she cried--I charge you, lose not my
sons! lose not atom;
And you streams, absorb them well, taking their dear blood;
And you local spots, and you airs that swim above lightly,
And all you essences of soil and growth--and you, my rivers' depths;
And you, mountain sides--and the woods where my dear children's
blood, trickling, redden'd;
And you trees, down in your roots, to bequeath to all future
trees, 10
My dead absorb--my young men's beautiful bodies absorb--and their
precious, precious, precious blood;
Which holding in trust for me, faithfully back again give me, many a
year hence,
In unseen essence and odor of surface and grass, centuries hence;
In blowing airs from the fields, back again give me my darlings--give
my immortal heroes;
Exhale me them centuries hence--breathe me their breath--let not an
atom be lost;
O years and graves! O air and soil! O my dead, an aroma sweet!
Exhale them perennial, sweet death, years, centuries hence.
